  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "A factory produces widgets with a 2% defect rate. If you sample 50 widgets, what's the expected number of defects and the probability of finding zero defects?",
  "response_text": "To solve this problem, we can use the properties of the binomial distribution. The binomial distribution is appropriate here because we have a fixed number of trials (n = 50), each with two possible outcomes (defective or not defective), and a constant probability of success (p = 2% or 0.02).\n\n### Expected Number of Defects\n\nThe expected value (mean) of a binomial distribution is given by:\n\\[ E(X) = n \\cdot p \\]\n\nSubstituting the values:\n\\[ E(X) = 50 \\cdot 0.02 = 1 \\]\n\nSo, the expected number of defects in a sample of 50 widgets is 1.\n\n### Probability of Finding Zero Defects\n\nThe probability of finding zero defects in a sample can be calculated using the binomial probability formula:\n\\[ P(X = k) = \\binom{n}{k} \\cdot p^k \\cdot (1-p)^{n-k} \\]\n\nFor \\( k = 0 \\):\n\\[ P(X = 0) = \\binom{50}{0} \\cdot (0.02)^0 \\cdot (0.98)^{50} \\]\n\nSince \\(\\binom{50}{0} = 1\\) and \\((0.02)^0 = 1\\), the equation simplifies to:\n\\[ P(X = 0) = (0.98)^{50} \\]\n\nCalculating this:\n\\[ P(X = 0) \\approx (0.98)^{50} \\approx 0.364 \\]\n\nSo, the probability of finding zero defects in a sample of 50 widgets is approximately 0.364 or 36.4%.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 7\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
